INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '92917377-cddf-4b79-97cf-1bc113e4961d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NestJS CLI — Scaffolding, Hot Reload, and Code Generation That Actually Saves Time$escape$,
  $escape$The NestJS CLI is more than `nest new`. Used properly, it eliminates boilerplate and keeps your feedback loop tight.

`nest generate resource payments` scaffolds a full CRUD module — controller, service, DTOs, entity, and module registration — in one command. Add `--no-spec` to skip test files when prototyping. For granular generation, `nest g interceptor logging --flat` drops the file directly into the current directory without a subdirectory.

For hot reload, NestJS doesn't use Vite or Webpack HMR by default — you wire it manually via `webpack-hmr`. Install `webpack` and `@types/webpack-env`, then call `webpack(config, (err, stats) => { if (module.hot) { module.hot.accept(); } })` inside `main.ts`. This preserves the DI container between saves, cutting cold-start overhead from ~3s to under 300ms on large projects.

In monorepos, `nest build` respects `nest-cli.json` project roots. Set `"compilerOptions": { "deleteOutDir": true }` to avoid stale compiled artifacts causing phantom import errors during development.$escape$,
  $escape$// main.ts — webpack HMR setup for NestJS
declare const module: any;

async function bootstrap() {
  const app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule);
  await app.listen(3000);

  if (module.hot) {
    module.hot.accept();
    module.hot.dispose(() => app.close());
  }
}
bootstrap();$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
